{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17496809","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17496809"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T08:56:47+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T08:56:47+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1421"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1421","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1421"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.03,0.28,0.3,0.36]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1421"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109721"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1421","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1421"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1421"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92118"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1984"},{"type":"tags","id":"4964"},{"type":"tags","id":"4965"},{"type":"tags","id":"9644"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1832"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1842"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7158"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13915"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15251"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18790"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43843"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109721","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/109721"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 56-year-old woman presents to her general practitioner with a three month history of progressive fatigue. She now feels tired and run down and these symptoms are affecting her daily life. She is post-menopausal, with her last period at age 48 and no recent episodes of bleeding. There has been no recent changes to her diet. She eats mainly vegetarian options, supplemented with fish. Her medical history includes rheumatoid arthritis, with her last exacerbation over five years ago. She does not currently have any joint pain. She is a non-smoker and drinks about three glasses of wine at weekends. The only medication she takes regularly is hydroxychloroquine which she has taken for over 20 years with no adverse effects.  Her preventative screening is up to date for her age and she has never had additional screening done. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThere are minor metacarpal joint changes on physical examination, however there are no other remarkable features. Some blood investigations are performed.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Rheumatology referral","Dietician referral","Faecal occult blood test (FOBT)","Oral iron supplementation","Arrange endoscopy and colonoscopy"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe patient has an iron deficiency anaemia with low serum iron and ferritin, whereas anaemia of chronic disease like that associated with rheumatoid arthritis would result in normal/high ferritin as it rises in inflammatory states. She has not complained of recent symptoms and her rheumatoid arthritis appears well managed therefore a \u003Cstrong\u003Erheumatology referral\u003C/strong\u003E is not required.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAs this is a symptomatic, postmenopausal woman with a significantly low haemoglobin, \u003Cstrong\u003Eoral iron supplementation\u003C/strong\u003E is insufficient. She requires further investigation. The most important next step in management is to identify the cause of the deficiency, particularly to look for sites of gastrointestinal bleeding associated with colorectal carcinoma. She could be bleeding from other sites in the gut and patients with rheumatoid arthritis may be taking NSAIDs. This makes \u003Cstrong\u003Eendoscopy and colonoscopy\u003C/strong\u003E the most appropriate option. Once this has been arranged, iron supplements could be given. Alternatively, she could be given an iron infusion at the time an intravenous line is inserted for her endoscopy and colonoscopy. This is the approach that many gastroenterologists would arrange.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMost cases of iron deficiency anaemia result from insufficient dietary intake or blood loss from the digestive tract. Menstrual bleeding is another important cause - but not in this case as she is postmenopausal. Whilst it is possible that the anaemia in the case of this patient could be \u003Cstrong\u003Ediet-related\u003C/strong\u003E, it would be unusual for her vegetarian lifestyle alone to explain the severity of the anaemia and other causes must be sought. \u003Cstrong\u003EFOBT\u003C/strong\u003E is a screening test and is not to be used for investigation of symptomatic patients and is therefore inappropriate in this scenario.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The finding of an iron-deficiency anaemia in an older patient must always raise the possibility of a gastrointestinal malignancy."],"references":["Camaschella C. Iron-Deficiency Anemia. N Engl J Med 2015; 372:1832-43.","Pasricha SR, Tye-Din J, Muckenthaler MU, Swinkels DW. Iron deficiency. Lancet. 2021 Jan 16;397(10270):233-248.","Soin, S., Akanbi, O., Ahmed, A. et al. Use and abuse of fecal occult blood tests: a community hospital experience. BMC Gastroenterol 19, 161 (2019).","Snook J, Bhala N, Beales ILP, et al. British Society of Gastroenterology guidelines for the management of iron deficiency anaemia in adults. Gut 2021; 0:1-22.","Gastroenterological Society of Australia. Iron deficiency - Clinical Update for General Practitioners and Physicians. 2022. Available at: https://www.gesa.org.au/public/13/files/Education%20%26%20Resources/Clinical%20Practice%20Resources/Iron%20Deficiency/Iron%20Deficiency%20Clinical%20Update%202022%20APPROVED.pdf"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92118"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1421"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"17760"},{"type":"media","id":"17761"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"17760","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/17760"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/0ee07ca1-6cfb-42e4-bac2-77c218e26f8a.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/0ee07ca1-6cfb-42e4-bac2-77c218e26f8a.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":800,"height":206}},{"type":"media","id":"17761","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/17761"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/148fb0da-82b1-4775-98d4-35cd50039e2e.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/148fb0da-82b1-4775-98d4-35cd50039e2e.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":800,"height":163}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92118","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/92118"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-25T18:08:15+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-25T18:08:15+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1421"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109721"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"e